graphs.title: For a Serious Relationship, You Need Serious Words
graphs.question: Is there a difference in the use of serious relationship keywords based on gender (male vs female)?
method: Profile text was tokenized into individual words and lowercased.
A curated set of words associated with serious relationship intent was defined.
Occurrences of these words were counted within each profile.
Serious words that followed a negation (e.g., 'not looking for a serious relationship') were excluded from counts.
Counts were normalized by total word count per profile to control for length differences.
Aggregate rates were compared across profiles using bar charts.
key_findings: Among male profiles, 200 out of 213 (93.90%) contained serious relationship language, compared to 90 out of 96 female profiles (93.75%).
This indicates a consistently high prevalence of serious relationship language across genders, with minimal difference between male and female profiles.
The widespread use of serious relationship language suggests shared dating intentions and similar communication styles across genders on DateMe Directory.
These patterns likely reflect the platform’s user base, which skews toward individuals in their late 20s to 40s who may be more interested in long-term relationships.

graphs.title: Excitement through Exclamation: Generational Differences in Exclamation Mark Usage
graphs.question: How does the use of exclamation points vary across different generations?
method: Profile text was scanned for exclamation points.
Total exclamation counts were calculated per profile.
Counts were normalized per 100,000 characters to account for profile length.
Profiles were grouped by generation. [Gen Z: born 1997-2012, Millennials: born 1981-1996, Gen X: born 1965-1980, Boomers: born 1946-1964]
Group-level averages were visualized to compare punctuation usage across generations.
key_findings: Exclamation mark usage per 100,000 words varies across generations, indicating meaningful differences in punctuation style.
Gen Z shows the highest exclamation mark rate, suggesting a more expressive or emphatic communication style relative to older cohorts.
Boomers show the lowest exclamation mark rate, which may reflect a more reserved or formal writing style; this result may also be influenced by smaller sample size for Boomers on the platform.
These generational patterns likely reflect differences in online communication norms and can inform how dating platforms tailor tone, prompts, or messaging features for different age groups.
Overall, punctuation behavior provides a lightweight signal of communication style that may correlate with how users present themselves in dating profiles.

graphs.title: Does Complexity Attract More Interest? Word Complexity Based on Gender Preferences
graphs.question: When gender preference changes, how does word complexity across genders (male, female, non-binary) change?
method: Profile text was tokenized into words and lowercased.
A word was classified as complex if it contained eight or more characters.
For each profile, complexity was calculated as the percentage of complex words.
Profiles were grouped by gender and by the genders they expressed interest in.
Profiles interested in multiple genders were included in multiple groups.
Distributions were summarized using medians and interquartile ranges and visualized as bar charts.
key_findings: Word complexity levels are broadly similar across groups, with most medians falling in the ~12–15% range of words meeting the complexity threshold.

Across all three target-gender graphs (looking for men, women, or non-binary people), profiles written by women show slightly higher word-complexity percentages than profiles written by men or non-binary users.
This consistent (though modest) gap suggests that women’s profiles may use longer or more complex words more frequently, regardless of who they are seeking.
Because differences are small, this should be interpreted as a subtle stylistic tendency rather than a major separation between groups.
A possible explanation is that profiles differ in tone or self-presentation strategies across genders, which can influence vocabulary choices; this analysis does not measure intent directly.

graphs.title: US vs Non-US Regional Word Differences
graphs.question: What are the most distinctive words used in US profiles and non-US profiles?
method: Profiles were split into US vs Non-US based on the selection on the location field.
Profile text was tokenized into lowercase word tokens (letters + apostrophes) and filtered to remove stopwords.
Only candidate words with length ≥ 6 and total frequency ≥ 5 across both groups were retained.
Distinctive words were identified using z-scored log-odds ratios with a Dirichlet prior (positive = US, negative = Non-US).
The top-ranked words for each group were exported to CSV and visualized as a two-column table figure.
key_findings: Using z-scored log-odds with a Dirichlet prior, several words were strongly distinctive for US profiles, including "google" (z=3.73), "business" (z=2.85), and "travel" (z=2.82).
Several words were strongly distinctive for Non-US profiles, including "london" (z=-4.20), "listening" (z=-3.15), and "interest" (z=-3.05).
Overall, the most distinctive US words skew toward tech/professional and leisure themes, while the most distinctive Non-US words skew toward place references and stated interests.

These differences highlight regional variation in self-presentation style and profile content, which can inform how dating platforms localize prompts, marketing, or onboarding to better match regional norms.
Because region classification is heuristic and the analysis focuses on relative word usage, findings should be interpreted as theme-level tendencies rather than fixed traits of individual users.

graphs.title: SF Bay Area vs UK/London Slang: Regional Word Differences
graphs.question: What are the most distinctive words used in SF Bay Area profiles and UK/London profiles?
method: Profiles were classified strictly into SF Bay Area vs UK/London using based on the selection on the location field.
Profile text was tokenized into lowercase word tokens (letters + apostrophes) and filtered to remove stopwords.
Only candidate words with length ≥ 6 and total frequency ≥ 5 across both regions were retained.
Distinctive words were identified using z-scored log-odds ratios with a Dirichlet prior (positive = Bay Area, negative = UK/London).
Top-ranked words for each region were exported to CSV and visualized as a two-column table with inline token counts.
key_findings: Several words were strongly distinctive for SF Bay Area profiles, including "favorite" (z=3.68), "working" (z=3.40), and "research" (z=3.21).
Several words were strongly distinctive for UK/London profiles, including "london" (z=-5.27), "fiction" (z=-3.74), and "berlin" (z=-3.52).

Overall, Bay Area profiles skew toward work/academia and partnership-oriented language (e.g., "research", "berkeley", "partnership", "relationships"), while UK/London profiles show more location and interest markers (e.g., "london", "travelling", "fiction") and British spelling ("favourite").

These differences highlight regional variation in self-presentation, where Bay Area users may foreground career/education and relationship framing, while UK/London users more often include place references and personal interests.
Because region classification is heuristic and the analysis captures relative word frequency, results should be interpreted as theme-level tendencies rather than fixed traits of individual users.

graphs.title: Sometimes, Em-Dashes aren't AI indicators. They Just Add Flair
graphs.question: How many em-dashes are used in profiles?
method: Profile text was extracted from profileDetails.fullText with fallbacks and profiles with empty text were excluded.
The Unicode em dash character (—) was counted per profile using exact character matching.
Profiles were optionally filtered by minimum word count (simple whitespace token count).
Counts were bucketed into 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, and 5+ (cap configurable).
Bucket counts and percentages were exported to CSV and visualized as a labeled bar chart.
key_findings: This chart was originally explored as a potential proxy for AI-generated text using em-dash (—) frequency.
After reviewing the results, em-dash presence did not show a meaningful relationship with AI-generated text in this dataset and was not used as an AI-likelihood measure.
The chart was therefore repurposed to summarize the distribution of em-dash usage across all profiles.
This distribution provides a baseline view of how frequently em-dashes appear in general profile writing and how concentrated usage is among a smaller subset of profiles.

graphs.title: Does Complexity Attract More Interest? Sentence Complexity Based on Gender Preferences
graphs.question: When gender preference changes, how does sentence complexity across genders (male, female, non-binary) change?
method: A sentence was defined as complex if it contained at least 21 words (threshold configurable).
For each profile, sentence complexity was calculated as the percent of sentences meeting the complexity threshold.
Profiles were grouped by source gender and by target gender of interest; multi-target profiles were included in multiple target groups.
Distributions were summarized with medians and interquartile ranges and visualized as IQR bars with median labels.
key_findings: Across groups, median sentence complexity (percent of sentences ≥ 21 words) generally falls in the mid-teens, with several groups showing substantial spread (wide IQRs and high maxima).
For profiles looking for men (target=M), medians are similar across source genders: Women 15.632% (n=94) vs Men 14.194% (n=17) vs NB 15.789% (n=3).
For profiles looking for women (target=F), Women have the highest median long-sentence rate at 25.965% (n=14), compared to Men at 14.629% (n=206) and NB at 18.919% (n=3).

For profiles looking for non-binary people (target=NB), Women again show higher median sentence complexity at 21.741% (n=16) relative to Men at 16.486% (n=26), though the NB source group is not interpretable (n=1).
Several categories have very small sample sizes (especially NB source groups), so those medians should be treated as descriptive rather than strong evidence of stable group differences.

graphs.title: Regional Slang Prevalence: SF Bay Area vs UK/London Wordsets
graphs.question: Are there SF Bay Area vs UK/London differences in the prevalence of words from Bay Area-specific wordsets compared to all US/non-US profiles?
method: Profile text was tokenized into words and lowercased.
Two curated wordsets representing SF Bay Area and UK/London vocabulary were defined.
Matches to each wordset were counted within each profile.
Counts were aggregated by location group and normalized per 10,000 tokens.
Rates were visualized as grouped bar charts to compare regional prevalence.
key_findings: Wordset prevalence patterns align strongly with region: Bay Area profiles show the highest Bay-wordset rate (370.29 per 10k tokens), while UK/London profiles show the highest UK-wordset rate (460.33 per 10k tokens).
Compared to the ALL_US baseline (Bay=262.74; UK=261.36 per 10k), Bay Area profiles over-index on Bay-wordset terms (370.29) but not on UK-wordset terms (257.83).
UK/London profiles show the opposite pattern: lower Bay-wordset usage (178.34) and substantially higher UK-wordset usage (460.33) relative to ALL_US.
This suggests the Bay and UK/London wordsets function as meaningful regional markers rather than general-purpose vocabulary.
Because rates are normalized per 10,000 tokens, differences are less likely to be driven by profile length and more likely to reflect real vocabulary selection.
